he level I've assigned—particularly for Behavior 3, where describing a real test execution would push it to System, but mocking the test runner keeps it at Integration. , Integration if we mock the runner. I should clarify.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully for behavior 3:\n\nThe real failure mode is: the orchestration layer must capture test failure output and pass it to the next LLM call. To test this without mocking:\n- First LLM call returns broken code\n- Test runner runs it, produces failures\n- Second LLM call receives those failures in prompt\n\nIf we mock the LLM but use real test execution, that's System (real code running in subprocess). If we mock both LLM and test runner, that's Integration (module wiring test).\n\nThe question is whether mocking the test runner hides real failures. Does the actual test runner output format matter? Yes - the code that parses test output could fail to capture the right format. But we can fake realistic test output in a mock.\n\nI'll say Integration is the minimum, since mocking the test runner with realistic failure output still validates the wiring. The failure mode (messages not included in prompt) is testable without real code execution.\n\nNow I'm assigning probabilities for each behavior. For behavior 1, the LLM needs to generate correct function signatures, which really requires agentic testing with a real model—mocking can't validate that claim. Behavior 2 involves multiple steps and iterative refinement, so workflow testing dominates. For behavior 3, I'm starting with the probability distribution across test levels.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9443,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9443},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5eb0cae4-fb5b-